After the Conquest, it is probable, for we can only speak doubtingly and hypo- thetically, that the heir obtained the Royal authority, at least sor the purposes of admi- nistering the law, from the day that his peace was proclaimed. He was obeyed as Chief Magistrate, so soon as he was admitted to the high office of protector of the public tranquillity. But he was not honoured as the King, until the sacred oil had been poured upon him, and the crown set upon his head, and the sceptre grasped in his hand.
